{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5ad0bd27-8685-4a45-970a-aba9cb465190","content":"The standard approach in .NET is to use **`System.IO.Abstractions`**:\n\n1. **Install the NuGet package** `System.IO.Abstractions`\n2. **Replace** direct `File.*` / `Directory.*` calls with an injected `IFileSystem` dependency:\n   ```csharp\n   public class MyService\n   {\n       private readonly IFileSystem _fs;\n       public MyService(IFileSystem fs) => _fs = fs;\n\n       public void Save(string path, string content)\n           => _fs.File.WriteAllText(path, content);\n   }\n   ```\n3. **In production**, register the real implementation:\n   ```csharp\n   services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem>(new FileSystem());\n   ```\n4. **In tests**, use the companion package `System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers`:\n   ```csharp\n   var fs = new MockFileSystem();\n   var svc = new MyService(fs);\n   svc.Save(\"/tmp/test.txt\", \"hello\");\n   Assert.Equal(\"hello\", fs.File.ReadAllText(\"/tmp/test.txt\"));\n   ```\n\nThis gives you `IFile`, `IDirectory`, `IPath`, etc. — drop-in replacements for every static in `System.IO`, fully mockable with no real disk I/O in tests.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8e90dfc4-dba8-454d-84da-257a418a7ef6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making file system operations testable in .NET. This is a general software engineering question about testability patterns, not a task requiring code changes. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":384,"requestId":"A039:362ABC:E763E0:10FB461:69FE9457"},"id":"2d6ad82c-fb5d-49e3-82e8-6dfe32525281","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:56:47.752Z","parentId":"61009adc-70eb-499d-b2e8-913814b3e78e"}
